## 4. Current Issues Found

### 🔴 Critical — Build-Breaking / Always Fail

#### C1. `moduleResolution: "bundler"` with `module: "CommonJS"` is Invalid

**Affects:** Every single [tsconfig.json](file:///d:/Sentinel/tsconfig.json) in the project (root, shared-utils, all 5 services, gateway)

TypeScript's `"bundler"` moduleResolution is designed **exclusively** for bundler-based setups (Vite, webpack). When using `module: "CommonJS"`, TypeScript mandates `moduleResolution: "node"` or `"node16"`.

**Fix:** Change `"moduleResolution": "bundler"` to `"moduleResolution": "node"` in every tsconfig.

---

#### C2. `@shared/utils` in `devDependencies` Instead of `dependencies`

**Affects:** [user-service/package.json](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/user-service/package.json), [incident-service/package.json](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/package.json)

These services import `@shared/utils` at runtime (e.g., `import { db } from "@shared/utils"`), but list it under `devDependencies`. In production Docker builds with `npm install --production`, this dependency won't be installed.

**Fix:** Move `"@shared/utils": "*"` from `devDependencies` to `dependencies`.

---

#### C3. Duplicate Kafka Producer in Incident Service

**Affects:** [incident-service/kafka/kafka.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/kafka.ts) and [incident-service/kafka/producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/producer.ts)

Two separate `kafka.producer()` instances are created:
- [kafka.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/kafka.ts) exports `producer` (used by [consumer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/audit-service/src/kafka/consumer.ts))
- [producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/audit-service/src/kafka/producer.ts) creates **another** `producer` (used by [incidents.controller.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/controllers/incidents.controller.ts))

The producer in [producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/audit-service/src/kafka/producer.ts) is **never connected** (its [initProducer()](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#7-11) is never called in [server.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/user-service/src/server.ts)). This means [sendIncidentEvent](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#12-27) will throw at runtime.

**Fix:** Remove the duplicate producer in [producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/audit-service/src/kafka/producer.ts). Import the shared producer from [kafka.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/kafka.ts) and use it everywhere.

---

#### C4. Kafka Message Key is a Static String

**Affects:** [firewall-service/kafka/producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#L21)

```typescript
key: "event.tempId",  // ← string literal, not the variable
```

This should be `key: event.tempId` (without quotes) to use the actual UUID as the partition key.

---

#### C5. [sanitizeLogs()](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/sanitizeLogs.ts#24-109) Returns Parsed Object, Not String

**Affects:** [firewall-service/kafka/producer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#L13)

[sanitizeLogs(db, log.message)](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/sanitizeLogs.ts#24-109) is called where the second argument should be the full `log` object, not just `log.message`. The function expects `logs: any` and does `JSON.stringify(sanitized)` / `JSON.parse(dataString)` — it returns a parsed JSON object, but `sanitizedSnippet` of [IncidentCreatedEvent](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/types.ts#1-11) expects a `string`.

---

#### C6. Gateway Service Registry Ports Are Wrong

**Affects:** [gateway/serviceRegistry.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/gateway/src/utils/serviceRegistry.ts)

| Service | Registry Port | Actual Port |
|---|---|---|
| users | 4002 | 4000 |
| firewall | 4003 | 4002 |
| ai | 4004 | N/A |

The ports don't match Docker Compose or service startup. The gateway will proxy to wrong services.

**Fix:** Correct the mapping:
```typescript
users: process.env.USER_SERVICE_URL || "http://localhost:4000",
firewall: process.env.FIREWALL_SERVICE_URL || "http://localhost:4002",
```

---

### 🟠 Major — Logic/Design Issues

#### M1. Firewall AI Worker Calls Itself via HTTP

**Affects:** [firewall-service/kafka/consumer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/kafka/consumer.ts#L27-28)

The Kafka consumer within the firewall service makes an HTTP call to `http://localhost:4002/api/analyze` (its own Express server). This creates a fragile self-loop. In Docker, `localhost` will fail since the consumer runs in the same container.

**Fix:** Import and call the AI analysis function directly instead of via HTTP, or use the Docker service name.

---

#### M2. Incident Service Has No HTTP Server

**Affects:** [incident-service/server.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/server.ts)

The incident service only starts Kafka consumers. It never creates an Express app or calls `app.listen()`. But the gateway proxies HTTP requests to `http://localhost:4001/incidents`. Those requests will fail.

It has routes, controllers, and helpers ready, but they're never mounted on an Express server.

**Fix:** Add Express server initialization alongside the Kafka consumers.

---

#### M3. User Service Missing `express.json()` Middleware

**Affects:** [user-service/server.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/user-service/src/server.ts)

No `app.use(express.json())` call. All POST/PATCH endpoints that read `req.body` will get `undefined`.

---

#### M4. `incident.created` Topic Conflict — Two Producers

The firewall service produces `incident.created` events via Kafka (the intended flow), but the incident-service controller also produces to `incident.created` via its REST API + [sendIncidentEvent()](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#12-27). These are different event schemas:
- Firewall produces [IncidentCreatedEvent](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/types.ts#1-11) (has `tempId`, `sanitizedSnippet`)
- Controller produces a raw [Incident](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/helpers/incidents.helpers.ts#3-16) object (has `title`, `description`)

The consumer expects [IncidentCreatedEvent](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/types.ts#1-11) shape. Events from the REST API will cause parse failures or silent data corruption.

---

#### M5. `alert.created` Fired Unconditionally

**Affects:** [incident-service/kafka/consumer.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/kafka/consumer.ts#L58-71)

Every analyzed incident produces an `alert.created` event with `severity: "high"` and a hardcoded message, regardless of the actual incident severity. This creates alert fatigue.

**Fix:** Only produce alerts when AI analysis reports high confidence + high severity.

---

#### M6. `redisClient` Event Listeners Re-Attached on Every Call

**Affects:** [shared-utils/redisClient.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/redisClient.ts)

[getRedisClient()](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/redisClient.ts#11-28) re-attaches `.on("connect")` and `.on("error")` handlers every time it's called. Over time, this leaks event listeners.

**Fix:** Move event listener attachment inside the `if (!redisClient)` block.

---

#### M7. Gateway Forwarding `req.headers` to Services

The gateway forwards raw `req.headers` (including `host`, `content-length`, etc.) to backend services via axios. This can cause request failures or misrouted requests because the `Host` header will refer to the gateway, not the service.

---

#### M8. Firewall Routes File Typo

**Affects:** filename [anayzer.routes.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/routes/anayzer.routes.ts) should be `analyzer.routes.ts`.

---

### 🟡 Moderate — Incomplete Implementations

#### I1. Firewall Ingest Controller Skips Sanitization

**Affects:** [firewall-service/controllers/ingestLogs.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/controllers/ingestLogs.ts)

The controller directly calls [produceCreateIncidentEvent(logs)](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/firewall-service/src/kafka/producer.ts#7-30) without any validation. The actual sanitization happens inside the producer function, which is a layer violation. The controller should validate and potentially batch the logs.

---

#### I2. [sanitizeLogs()](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/sanitizeLogs.ts#24-109) — Commented-Out System Events & Alerts

**Affects:** [shared-utils/sanitizeLogs.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/sanitizeLogs.ts#L76-103)

System event recording and alert creation for policy violations are commented out. The function only records `policy_logs`.

---

#### I3. No `ingest.analyzed` or Policy Violation Events

Per your architecture, the firewall should produce `ingest.analyzed` and policy violation events. Currently it only produces `incident.created`. Policy violations are logged to the DB but not emitted as Kafka events.

---

#### I4. Audit-Service & Notification-Service Have No HTTP Server

Neither service exposes an HTTP endpoint. Docker Compose maps ports 4003 and 4004 and the gateway has env vars for `AUDIT_SERVICE_URL` and `NOTIFICATION_SERVICE_URL`, but no routes exist for them. Health checks will fail.

---

#### I5. Incident-Service Auth Middleware & Rate Limiter — Unused

The incident service has [authMiddleware.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/middlewares/authMiddleware.ts) and [rateLimiter.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/services/incident-service/src/middlewares/rateLimiter.ts) but neither is used (no Express app exists).

---

#### I6. [knexfile.root.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/knexfile.root.ts) Imports Wrong Export

[knexfile.root.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/knexfile.root.ts) does `import {knexConfig} from "@shared/utils"` but [db/knexfile.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/db/knexfile.ts) uses `export default knexConfig` which is not re-exported as a named export from [index.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/src/gateway/src/index.ts) — it's re-exported as `export * from "./db/knexfile"` which brings in the default as... nothing (default exports are not re-exported by `export *`).

---

#### I7. [.env](file:///d:/Sentinel/.env) Path Resolution May Fail in Docker

[shared-utils/env.ts](file:///d:/Sentinel/packages/shared-utils/src/env.ts) resolves [.env](file:///d:/Sentinel/.env) via `path.resolve(__dirname, "../../../.env")`. In Docker, `__dirname` will be a `dist/` folder and `../../../.env` may not resolve to the correct path. Docker Compose already provides env vars, so this won't crash Docker—but it makes local development fragile.

---

